<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Almost certainly related to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procumbens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea procumbens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="longirostra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. longirostra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its ovate-deltoid, basally truncate leaves which are borne on slender pedicels. The subequal sepals are ovate-elliptic with distinct scarious margins, rather different from the lanceolate to ovate, usually acute to acuminate sepals of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procumbens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. procumbens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The strongly rostrate capsule of the new species is also striking.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C.R. Sperling et al. 6050</emphasis>
